    en: "A New York landlord cannot punish a tenant for using legal rights — reporting code violations, joining a tenant association, demanding repairs, or filing a housing court case. Real Property Law 223-b creates a presumption of retaliation when the landlord serves an eviction, a nonrenewal, a rent hike, or a cut in services within one year of a protected complaint. A tenant who proves retaliation has a defense to eviction, can have a retaliatory rent increase undone, and can recover damages. The statute applies to landlords of four or more residential units at a property; common-law retaliation principles can still reach smaller buildings."
